category: "Pediatrics",
subcategory: "01-neonatology",
tags: ["PYQ", "NEET PG 2024"],
text: "A 3-month-old baby with intracranial diffuse calcifications, chorioretinitis, and hydrocephalus. What is the most likely diagnosis?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Toxoplasmosis", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "B", "text": "CMV", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Zika virus", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Rubella", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Congenital toxoplasmosis classically presents with the triad of chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus, and intracranial calcifications.<br><br>* Caused by transplacental infection with Toxoplasma gondii\n* Intracranial calcifications are typically diffuse (not periventricular)\n* Associated features include seizures, developmental delay, and hepatosplenomegaly<br><br>**Differentiation:**<br><br>* **CMV:** periventricular calcifications\n* **Zika virus:** microcephaly with calcifications\n* **Rubella:** cataracts, cardiac defects, deafness",
